# 📌 1. Project Overview

This project analyses the relationship between:
- Mortality rate (`val`)
- Education level (`edu_name`)
- Age group (`age_name`)
- Geographic location (`location_name`)

using **IHME datasets (2018 & 2019)** in a **Databricks Lakehouse architecture**.

---

# 🏗️ 2. Environment Setup (Azure Databricks)

## Step 1 — Create Workspace
- Azure Portal → Azure Databricks → Create Workspace
- Pricing Tier: Trial / Standard
- Region: UK South

## Step 2 — Create Cluster
- Go to **Compute → Create Cluster**
- Node type: `Standard_D4pds_v6`
- Mode: **Single Node** (to avoid quota error)
- Auto terminate: 30 minutes

---

# 📂 3. Data Upload

## Method Used: Databricks UI

- Go to:

Workspace → Add Data → Create or modify table

- Upload files:
- `ihme_deaths_education_2018.csv`
- `ihme_deaths_education_2019.csv`

---

# 🔹 4. Data Ingestion (PySpark)

```python
path_2018 = "/Volumes/catalog/schema/volume/ihme_deaths_education_2018.csv"
path_2019 = "/Volumes/catalog/schema/volume/ihme_deaths_education_2019.csv"

df18 = (spark.read
  .option("header", "true")
  .option("inferSchema", "true")
  .csv(path_2018))

df19 = (spark.read
  .option("header", "true")
  .option("inferSchema", "true")
  .csv(path_2019))

print(df18.count(), df19.count())
df18.printSchema()


🔹 5. Combine Datasets

df = df18.unionByName(df19)


🔹 6. Silver Layer — Data Cleaning

Remove unwanted rows
from pyspark.sql.functions import col

df_clean = df.filter(
    (col("edu_name") != "All educational attainment populations") &
    (col("val").isNotNull())
)
Drop unnecessary columns
drop_cols = [
    "measure_id","measure_name","location_id","fips",
    "edu_id","sex_id","cause_id","cause_name",
    "metric_id","metric_name","sex_name"
]

silver_clean = df_clean.drop(*drop_cols)
Save Silver Table
silver_clean.write \
    .format("delta") \
    .mode("overwrite") \
    .saveAsTable("com745_edu_mortality.silver_mortality_clean")


🔹 7. Gold Layer — Aggregations

7.1 Mortality by Education
from pyspark.sql.functions import avg

silver = spark.table("com745_edu_mortality.silver_mortality_clean")

gold_edu = (
    silver.groupBy("edu_name")
    .agg(avg("val").alias("avg_mortality_rate"))
    .orderBy("avg_mortality_rate", ascending=False)
)

display(gold_edu)
7.2 Age × Education
gold_age_edu = (
    silver.groupBy("age_name", "edu_name")
    .agg(avg("val").alias("avg_mortality_rate"))
)

display(gold_age_edu)
7.3 Geographic Aggregation
gold_location = (
    silver.groupBy("location_name", "edu_name")
    .agg(avg("val").alias("avg_mortality_rate"))
)

display(gold_location)
7.4 Top 50 Counties with Lowest Mortality
from pyspark.sql.functions import col

top50_least_mortality_overall = (
    gold_location
    .orderBy(col("avg_mortality_rate").asc())
    .limit(50)
)

display(top50_least_mortality_overall)


🔹 8. SQL Insights

Open SQL Cell:

Insight A — Education Gradient (2018 vs 2019)

SELECT
  year,
  edu_name,
  ROUND(AVG(val), 4) AS avg_mortality_rate,
  ROUND(AVG(lower), 4) AS avg_lower,
  ROUND(AVG(upper), 4) AS avg_upper
FROM com745_edu_mortality.silver_mortality_clean
WHERE year IN (2018, 2019)
GROUP BY year, edu_name
ORDER BY edu_name, year;
Insight B — Change (2018 → 2019)
WITH x AS (
  SELECT
    year,
    edu_name,
    AVG(val) AS avg_mortality_rate
  FROM com745_edu_mortality.silver_mortality_clean
  WHERE year IN (2018, 2019)
  GROUP BY year, edu_name
),
p AS (
  SELECT
    edu_name,
    MAX(CASE WHEN year = 2019 THEN avg_mortality_rate END) -
    MAX(CASE WHEN year = 2018 THEN avg_mortality_rate END) AS change_18_19
  FROM x
  GROUP BY edu_name
)
SELECT
  edu_name,
  ROUND(change_18_19, 4) AS change_18_19
FROM p
ORDER BY ABS(change_18_19) DESC;


📊 9. Visualisations (Databricks UI)

Visual 1 — Education Gradient
Type: Bar chart
X: edu_name
Y: avg_mortality_rate
Visual 2 — Age × Education
Type: Heatmap
X: edu_name
Y: age_name
Color: avg_mortality_rate
Visual 3 — Top 50 Counties
Type: Table
Sorted by: avg_mortality_rate ascending
Visual 4 — Year Comparison
Type: Bar chart
X: edu_name
Y: avg_mortality_rate
Group by: year


🔍 10. Key Insights

Mortality decreases with higher education
Age increases mortality significantly
Education disparity persists across all ages
Geographic clustering exists
Small but measurable changes between 2018 and 2019


